'''Charles Gosse''' (26 December 1849 &ndash; 1 July 1885) was a surgeon in the early days of the colony of [[South Australia]].

==Youth and Career==
Charles Gosse was born in [[Hoddesdon]], [[Hertfordshire]], the youngest son of the surgeon [[William Gosse (surgeon)|William Gosse]] who, in the hopes of curing his [[bronchitis]], brought his family to Australia in 1850, arriving in [[Adelaide, South Australia|Adelaide]] on 31 December. Charles followed his brother [[William Gosse (explorer)|William "Willie"]] in John  L. Young's [[Adelaide Educational Institution]], where he proved an apt pupil, being prominent at most prizegivings between 1857 and 1861. He was sent to England for further education; first at [[Clifton College]] in [[Bristol]], then at [[Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust|Moorfields Hospital]] where he served as a Clinical Clerk and gained his M.R.C.S. in 1870.<ref name=death/> He studied medicine at [[Charing Cross Hospital]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39193286 |title=Medical Studennts |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=15 June 1868 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> was admitted to the [[Royal College of Surgeons]] in 1870, and graduated with [[Bachelor of Medicine]] and [[Master of Surgery]] from the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1872.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39263218 |title= South Australians in England |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=29 July 1872 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He returned to Adelaide in 1873 and was promptly taken into partnership with his father.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39306539 |title=Notice of Partnership |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=8 April 1873 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on [[North Terrace, Adelaide|North Terrace]], and received his M.D. from Aberdeen in 1875. He was appointed to the Board of Management of the [[Royal Adelaide Hospital|Adelaide Hospital]] in 1877. He was appointed ophthalmic surgeon to the Adelaide Hospital in 1881 and made the third member of its Medical Committee in 1883.

South Australia had at the time a poor record of childhood mortality, with some 20% of infants dying within three months of birth, and Charles Gosse made it the subject of his special interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42981586 |title=Why Babies Die in South Australia |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=10 May 1878 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

On 29 June 1885 he was involved in a serious accident: he was riding in one of John Hill & Co's "[[Victoria (carriage)|victoria]]" carriages, driven by one John Lambert (who died in 1889 as the result of an unrelated accident),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54171945 |title=Out among the People. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|The Register News-Pictorial (Adelaide, SA : 1929 - 1931)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=23 January 1931 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> along Hutt Street with his daughter when one of the two horses shied, a pair of wheels broke, and the vehicle overturned, crushing his ankle under a footplate.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36309208 |title=Serious Accident to Dr. Gosse |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The South Australian Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1858 - 1889)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=30 June 1885 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Despite attention from the best medical men of the day, gangrene set in and Dr. Gosse died two days later after amputation of his leg.<ref name=death>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article44944236 |title=The Death of Dr. Charles Gosse. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=2 July 1885 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

His successor as ophthalmic surgeon at the Adelaide Hospital and elsewhere was taken by Dr. Mark Johnston Symons (1853 &ndash; 26 February 1927).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54884826 |title=OBITUARY. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|The Register (Adelaide, SA : 1901 - 1929)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=28 February 1927 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=11 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Interests==
Charles Gosse was a keen and accomplished cricketer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39823049 |title=Cricket |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=9 February 1874 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

He was elected to the committee of the Institute for the Blind, Deaf and Dumb in 1881 and the Home for Incurables in 1883.

He was appointed to the Medical Board in 1884<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43804884 |title=New Member of the Medical Board |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=11 December 1884 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> but retired in favour of Dr. Mayo.<ref name=death/>

He was a vice-president of the Church of England Institute

He was a director of [[Mutual Life Assurance]] of Australasia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article77507626 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[Border Watch|Border Watch (Mount Gambier, SA : 1861 - 1954)]] |location=Mount Gambier, SA |date=1 October 1884 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

He was a connoisseur of fine china, especially [[Minton ware]], of which he had a fine collection, all auctioned after his death.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26245766 |title=An Old Minton China Tea-set,. |newspaper=[[Perth Gazette|The West Australian (Perth, WA : 1879 - 1954)]] |location=Perth, WA |date=27 December 1909 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Family==
On 11 May 1880 he married Mary Blanche Hawker (1858 &ndash; 10 December 1945), daughter of [[George Charles Hawker]] M.P.
*daughter (17 March 1881 &ndash; )
Their home was on North Terrace and he had a summer residence "Thorpe" at Waverley Ridge, [[Mount Lofty, South Australia|Mount Lofty]]. After his death, his widow and daughter left for Italy then London, where they remained.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article56494507 |title=Personal Notes from England |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|The Register (Adelaide, SA : 1901 - 1929)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=14 March 1904 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Recognition==

On his death a committee was formed to establish a Charles Gosse Memorial fund, which established a Chair of Ophthalmic Surgery at the University of Adelaide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article44574469 |title=Charles Gosse Memorial |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=3 July 1886 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> From 1916 an annual Dr. Charles Gosse medal was awarded to the best candidate in the ophthalmology.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59910705 |title=Adelaide University Senate. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|The Register (Adelaide, SA : 1901 - 1929)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=23 November 1916 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Among the recipients of this enduring award was [[Neville Way]], who was also a noted player of [[Australian Rules]] football<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43794412 |title=Footballer Tops Medical School |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 - 1954)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=7 December 1948 |accessdate=25 May 2012 |page=1 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and Percival Francis Leitch Hussey who was also a noted yachtsman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47600580 |title=Death Of Dr. Hussey |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 - 1954)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=13 November 1954 |accessdate=25 May 2012 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

His portrait was photographed by [[Townsend Duryea]] around 1880.<ref>http://images.slsa.sa.gov.au/mpcimg/11500/B11307.htm</ref>

[[John Upton (painter)|John Alfred Upton]] (1850 &ndash; ) was commissioned by the Charles Gosse Memorial committee to paint his portrait in oils from a photograph, to be hung in the Ophthalmic ward of the Adelaide Hospital.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53629209 |title=The Development of Art |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=28 October 1893 |accessdate=25 May 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

